Abstract:

This study examined the relationship between happiness (In this study is represented by the Life Ladder Rank, a higher score represents a happier general population) and life expectancy by examining various social and economic factors across all five continents, thereby trying to answer the general questions: How would someone maximize his/her life expectancy or happiness? Does happiness have a relationship with life expectancy?. These questions are explored through several follow up questions, such as Does a change in life expectancy reflect a similar change in happiness?, Are these economic and social variables provided in the World Happiness Report related to life expectancy?, Which variable affects life expectancy and happiness the most?, Does Geography have an impact on life expectancy and happiness?. The questions were examined through creating and observing graphics and linear regression models based on the variables given, due to the large amount of numeric data in the datasets. Results showed that through finding and observing the p-values of the two linear models and the Q-Q plots for checking the model assumption, there is a positive relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness. Furthermore, despite a steady increase in both Life Expectancy and Happiness throughout all five continents, Oceania has stayed consistently higher in both regards, and Africa has remained the lowest. Additionally, while all economic and social variables are significant in relation to life expectancy with the exception of Freedom to make life choices, we have observed that Social Support is the most impactful variable for Happiness, and the second most impactful variable for Life Expectancy. These results have important implications for countries hoping to raise their life Expectancy and Happiness, but also answers the question, that there is a correlation between Nordic countries consistent high happiness and their social welfare program.

Overview and Motivation:

Throughout history, humans often struggle to find the solution to extend their mortality or even immortality. From inventing elixirs to offering sacrifices, yet we have seldom heard of those who have achieved this goal, yet various cultures across the globe have attempted it. Advancing into the 21st century, when many viral and bacterial diseases are preventable and infant mortality rate has dropped drastically, we pursue the question again, what is the secret to longevity? Is happiness the key?. Moreover, Nordic countries have consistently claimed the top seats in the World Happiness Report while maintaining a unique social welfare program. In this study, we hope to explore the reason, the variable with the highest impact, on Happiness.

In the following report, we have analyzed three important datasets, The World Happiness Report powered by data from Gallup World Poll, Global Life Expectancy collected from ourworldindata.org, and a dataset containing various countries and their respective continents via datahub.io, to discover the relationships between Global Life Expectancy and Global Happiness (represented by the Life Ladder Rank) and its various subsequent economic and social factors. We have discovered these relationships through combining datasets and cleaning the data, selecting specific response variables, finding significant explanatory variables, utilizing graphs to show the relationship between response and all explanatory variables, checking model assumptions and model building and showing the influence of significant explanatory variables vs.the response variable.

Related Work:

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31451635/

This study was inspired by Optimism is associated with exceptional longevity in 2 epidemiologic cohorts of men and women, a study conducted by numerous researchers such as Lewina O Lee, Peter James, Emily S. Zevon, etc. This research tested whether higher optimism was associated with longer life span and greater likelihood of exceptional longevity. The researchers analyzed data from two large population studies: the Nurses Health Study of 70,000 women, and the Veterans Affairs Normative Aging Study of 1,400 men. It also analyzed Happiness through the Life Orientation Test from the Nurses Health Study and the Optimism-Pessimism Scale from the Normative Aging study. The researchers found that for both men and women, higher levels of optimism were associated with a longer life span. This study inspired us as the results had shown that optimism did have a relationship with longevity. Therefore, we hoped to expand the study from optimism to general Happiness and the focus from only the United States to a more global perspective. After reading the study, we hoped to explore whether Happiness, in our study represented by the Life Ladder rank, is related to life expectancy.

Initial Questions:

The study attempts to find the relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness through exploring the following questions: Are all Social and Economic variables such as GDP, Social Support, Freedom of Choice, Healthy Life Expectancy at birth, Generosity, Perceptions of corruption, Positive affect, and Negative affect related to Life Expectancy?, What is the relationship between Geography (continent) and Life Expectancy?, What is the relationship between Geography (continent) and Happiness?, Do happy people live longer? If so, which variable affects both life expectancy and Life Ladder rank the most?, and finally Does a change in life expectancy reflect a similar change in Happiness?.

In its initial stages, the study also hoped to explore the relationship between COVID-19 cases across the world and each countrys socio-economic variables as well as global happiness. However, due to COVID-19 being a very recent event, and its long-lasting socio-economic impacts, it was decided after consideration to exclude these questions and the datasets all together, and instead focusing on further exploring the relationship between Life Expectancy and Happiness. This allowed us to explore the last two questions, and further examine how both the socio-economic variables and happiness impact life expectancy.

In the final stages of the project, we began to brainstorm additional questions for the project or future research and exploration. We planned to utilize predicting modelling and only a section of both given datasets to predict the relationship between life expectancy and happiness in the future. Therefore, we established the following question: Knowing both the Happiness scores and Life Expectancy of all five continents from 2010 to 2019, how will Happiness and Life Expectancy change in 2020. We believed this was an important question because we know that COVID-19 would create a global impact throughout 2020 and cause drastic changes. However, in the case that this event was miraculously avoided through early social distancing, quarantining and various other protective measures, would the relationship between Geography, Life Expectancy and Happiness still remain the same? However, we failed to pursue this question due to time constraints, but hope to pursue this question in a follow up study.

lifeExpectancy_world <- read_csv("./data/lifeExpectancy_world.csv")
world_happiness_report <- read_csv("./data/world-happiness-report.csv")
continent_country_tag <- read.csv("./data/country-and-continent-codes-list-csv_csv.csv")

Here, we imported 3 csv files and stored them with respective names. Two of them are sourced from kaggle, and the other is datahub.io

continent_country_tag <- continent_country_tag %>% rename("Code" = Three_Letter_Country_Code)
data <- lifeExpectancy_world %>% 
  rename("Country name" = Entity) %>% 
  pivot_longer(3:72, names_to = "year", values_to = "Expectancy") %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) %>% 
  filter(year >= 2008) %>% 
  left_join(world_happiness_report) %>% 
  left_join(continent_country_tag, by = "Code") %>% 
  na.omit()

Secondly, we took out all the variables with P-value larger than 0.05 from the model and named it as fit_significant. Since the p-value of the Anova test is greater than 0.05; therefore, the two models are adequate, we choose the second model which contains less variables. The p-values of all the variables are smaller than 5% in the second model support our decision as well. A significant variable means that it brings in true impact and the response variable.

plot(fit_significant, which = 2)

Finally, we check the model assumption with QQ plot, and it shows that the normality assumption is valid since the majority of residuals are along with the diagonal.

Question 2

Question: What is the relationship between continents and life expectancy?

Initial Results:

data %>% 
  select(Expectancy, Continent_Name, `year`) %>% 
  group_by(Continent_Name) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, Expectancy ,color = Continent_Name)) + 
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Relationship Between Geography and Life Expectancy") +
  labs(color = "Continent Name") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Life Expectancy")

First, we selected the variables that we interested in, and then grouped by the continents name. Secondly, we demonstrated the relationship with ggplot() function. Since we are interested in Life Expectancy, which is a continuous variable, and continents, which is a categorical variable, we also included a continuous variable, year, in order to make a reasonable plot. Based on the observation, there is definitely a relationship as different continents have drastically different life expectancy rates. Oceania has the highest life expectancy, followed by Europe, South America, North America, Asia and then subsequently Africa over time. We can also see that life expectancy for all continents have increased over time.

This could be due to some drastic events which needs further investigation.

Question 5

Question: Does a change in life expectancy reflect a similar change in happiness?

Initial Results:

fit1 <- lm(Expectancy ~ `Life Ladder`, data = data)
tidy(fit1)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term          estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>            <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)      43.2      0.750      57.6 0        
## 2 `Life Ladder`     5.34     0.137      39.0 2.85e-223
plot(fit1, which = 2)

fit2 <- lm(`Life Ladder` ~ Expectancy, data = data)
tidy(fit2)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  -1.76     0.184       -9.55 5.79e- 21
## 2 Expectancy    0.0991   0.00254     39.0  2.85e-223
plot(fit2, which = 2)

Here, we built two linear regression models with Life Expectancy and Life Ladder Happiness as the response variable respectively but with only 1 exploratory variable Life Expectancy or Life Ladder Happiness. Then, we check the model assumption with QQ plot, and it shows that the normality assumption is valid since the majority of residuals are along with the diagonal line. Both models have p-values less than 5% for Life Ladder and Expectancy, meaning these two variables are significant in both models. Looking at the estimate variable, both maintain a positive relationship. To interpret the relationship, we say 1 unit increase in Life Ladder Ranking would increase 5.5 years in life expectancy. Similarly, 1 unit increase in Life Expectancy would increase 0.094781 in Life Ladder Ranking.

data %>% select(`Life Ladder`, Expectancy, Continent_Name) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = `Life Ladder`, y = Expectancy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = Continent_Name)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  ggtitle("Life Expectancy vs Happiness") +
  xlab("Happiness") +
  ylab("Life Expectancy") +
  labs("Continent Name")

Here, we demonstrated the plot of Life Ladder Happiness against Expectancy. Comparing with the plot of Expectancy against Life Ladder Happiness in Question 4, we noticed that they both have positive relationship.
